article.description: Tamika Catchings scored 29 points and Coquese Washington added 13 as the Indiana Fever beat the New York Liberty 73-55 on Friday night for the first playoff victory in franchise history.
article.headline: Catchings propels Fever to first playoff win

images.caption: That's the Fever's Nadine Malcom in the middle of two Liberty defenders.

article.linkText: Liberty no match for top rookie Catchings
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Tamika Catchings backed up the WNBA Rookie of the Year Award with a dominating performance in her first playoff game.
Thursday, June 27
Vickie Johnson scored just four points and Tari Phillips only added six, so those two players need to contribute more offensively for the Liberty.

But New York didn't play as badly as everyone thinks. Indiana played very well and followed and executed coach Nell Fortner's game plan.

Indiana shot 51 percent, committed only 13 turnovers and outrebounded New York. And when you dominate the major statistical categories, good things are going to happen.

For Indiana, Tamika Catchings was unbelievable. She can go left or right, pull up and handle the ball. She's second on the team in assists.

Coquese Washington also put in another solid performance, and with the Fever going 9-3 since she was acquired from Houston, she's obviously giving Indiana something it was missing.
Catchings had 29 points, 11 rebounds, four 3-pointers, four assists and three steals as the Indiana Fever beat New York 73-55 on Friday night for the franchise's first playoff victory. "You know, she never ceases to amaze me,'' Fever coach Nell Fortner said. "She keeps coming up with good basketball plays. She was feeling it tonight.'' Game 2 of the best-of-three Eastern Conference semifinal series is Sunday in New York, and Game 3, if necessary, also would be at Madison Square Garden on Tuesday night. Indiana beat New York, the conference's top seed, for just the second time in three years. In those two victories, Catchings has scored 61 points. The Fever outshot the Liberty, outrebounded them and dominated a team that had been to the playoffs each of the last three years and has made three previous appearances in the WNBA Finals. Then they celebrated in front of the 10,198 fans who chanted "M-V-P! M-V-P!'' for Catchings, selected the WNBA's Rookie of the Year earlier Friday, throughout the second half. Indiana savored its seventh victory in eight games, as players smiled and hopped around -- long before the game ended. "We came out real enthusiastic,'' Catchings said. "Being our first playoff game with the fans here, we went out and pushed the ball and you saw happened.'' The Liberty could not keep up. They were led by Tamika Whitmore with 18 points. Crystal Robinson was the only other player to reach double figures, finishing with 10 points. But what appeared most troubling to coach Richie Adubato was that his team looked a step slow, hardly challenged the Fever and couldn't do anything to stop Catchings. The result was another loss, the Liberty's fifth in six games, and the franchise's worst playoff loss ever. "I don't understand it. We had a couple days off, but they certainly had all the intensity, they were pushing the ball, they were running,'' he said. "And we had no answer for Catchings, none.'' Catchings took advantage. Less than two hours after receiving her award, she turned in a performance worthy of it -- in front of her father, former NBA player Harvey Catchings. Catchings scored, rebounded, played defense, was the early catalyst for Indiana, and she put the finishing touches on the victory. In the first half alone, Catchings was 6-of-8 with three 3-pointers and 18 points as the Fever broke to a 35-24 lead. "This girl is crazy, her game is just sick,'' said Coquese Washington, who added 13 points. "It's ridiculous and on top of all that talent, she plays so hard.'' Even when the Liberty turned the focus to stopping Catchings early in the second half, the Fever found other answers. Washington scored just two first-half points but got going early in the second half when she hit a 3-pointer, drew a foul and completed a four-point play to make it 44-28. "I've never had a four-point play,'' Washington said. "That was pretty exciting.'' Washington followed that with a layup and another 3-pointer, making it 49-30 with 14:46 to go. New York responded with seven straight points, making its last run of the night. But the Fever got a putback and a three-point play from Kelly Schumacher and a 17-footer from Washington to rebuild a 56-39 lead. Then Catchings closed the door. After returning to the game, she scored six straight points for Indiana, making it 64-43 and ending any chance of a New York comeback. "All I wanted to do was stay active in the offense,'' Catchings said. "Even if I wouldn't have scored, I wanted to dish the ball out to players, just do anything to stay active.''
